# Debugging and Logging Standards

## Debug Logging
Use the standardized debug logging utility:
```typescript
function debugLog(
  level: "info" | "warn" | "error",
  message: string,
  data?: any
) {
  if (DEBUG) {
    const timestamp = new Date().toISOString();
    const emoji = level === "info" ? "ℹ️" : level === "warn" ? "⚠️" : "🚨";
    console.log(`${emoji} [${timestamp}] ${message}`);
    if (data) {
      console.log(JSON.stringify(data, null, 2));
    }
  }
}
```

## Log Levels
Use appropriate log levels:
- `info`: Regular operation information
- `warn`: Potential issues that don't affect operation
- `error`: Critical issues that affect operation

## Function Entry/Exit Logging
Log function entry/exit for key operations:
```typescript
async function importantOperation(params: Params) {
  const fnId = randomUUID();
  debugLog("info", `[${fnId}] Starting operation`, { params });
  
  try {
    const result = await doWork();
    debugLog("info", `[${fnId}] Operation completed`, { result });
    return result;
  } catch (error) {
    debugLog("error", `[${fnId}] Operation failed`, { error });
    throw error;
  }
}
```

## Error Logging
- Include stack traces in development
- Sanitize sensitive data
- Use consistent error formats
- Include correlation IDs

## Performance Logging
Log performance metrics:
```typescript
const start = performance.now();
// ... operation ...
debugLog("info", "Operation timing", {
  duration: performance.now() - start
});
```

## Environment-Specific Logging
- Use DEBUG environment variable
- Adjust detail level by environment
- Configure log destinations
- Implement log rotation

## Security Logging
- Log authentication attempts
- Track API usage
- Monitor rate limits
- Log security events
